  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">William Lloyd Garrison wants a character reference for a colored orphan boy named John brought to Boston by George (Thompson Garrison?). S. Waterhouse of Ellsworth, Maine, wants to hire the boy. Garrison wants to verify S. Waterhouse&apos;s character before sending the lad to him. Garrison&apos;s trip to Vergennes, Vermont, was pleasant; he received three &quot;rousing cheers at the conclusion&quot; of his address. After the meeting, Garrison was entertained by Rowland T. Robinson of Ferrisburgh, Vermont. Garrison mentions his projected western lecture tour and the opening meeting of the National Freedmen&apos;s Aid Commission. Garrison writes: &quot;If the rebel States, &apos;reconstructed&apos; so as to leave the colored people at the mercy of the savage whites, are suddenly admitted into the Union, there will assuredly be a terrible state of affairs, perhaps leading to a war of extermination.&quot;</subfield>
